===Kosovo dispute===
{{main|Political status of Kosovo|Kosovo status process}}
On 17 February 2008, the [[Kosovo]] parliament unilaterally [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|proclaimed independence]] from Serbia to mixed international reactions. The declaration was officially recognized by the U.S., Austria, Great Britain, Germany, France, Turkey and dozen other countries. Serbia, Russia, China, Spain, India, Brazil, Greece, Romania and other countries oppose this declaration and consider it illegal. In July 2010, the United Nations International Court of Justice deemed the separation of Kosovo legal, and Kosovo officials plan a 2011 application to the UN.<ref>http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/93190</ref><ref>http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/newsbriefs/setimes/newsbriefs/2010/07/25/nb-04</ref>

===EU integration===
{{main|Accession of Serbia to the European Union}}

Serbia officially applied for [[European Union]] membership on 22 December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.se2009.eu/en/meetings_news/2009/12/22/serbia_applies_for_eu_membership|title=Serbia applies for EU membership|publisher=Swedish Presidency of the European Union|accessdate=25 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> 

Despite its setbacks in the political field, on 7 December 2009 the EU unfroze the trade agreement with Serbia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europeanforum.net/news/791/eu_unfreezes_trade_agreement_with_serbia|title=EU unfreezes trade agreement with Serbia|accessdate=25 December 2009}}</ref> and the Schengen countries dropped the visa requirement for Serbian citizens on 19 December 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8387938.stm|title=EU scraps visas for three Balkan states|publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 December 2009 | date=1 December 2009}}</ref>

A [[Stabilisation and Association Agreement]] (SAA) was signed in 2008 and is expected to enter into force in 2011.

